SIMPLE: sail
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sail
<hw>Sail</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>seil</ets>, AS.
<ets>segel</ets>, <ets>segl</ets>; akin to D. <ets>zeil</ets>, OHG.
<ets>segal</ets>, G. & Sw. <ets>segel</ets>, Icel. <ets>segl</ets>, Dan.
<ets>seil</ets>. ⟦root⟧ 153.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An extent of canvas
or other fabric by means of which the wind is made serviceable as a
power for propelling vessels through the water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Behoves him now both <qex>sail</qex> and oar.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything resembling a sail, or regarded as a
sail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A wing; a van.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like an eagle soaring⟦br⟧
To weather his broad <qex>sails</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The extended surface of the arm of a
windmill.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A sailing vessel; a vessel of any kind; a
craft.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense, the plural has usually the same form as
the singular; <as>as, twenty <ex>sail</ex> were in
sight</as>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A passage by a sailing vessel; a journey or
excursion upon the water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Sails are of two general kinds, <stype>fore-and-aft
sails</stype>, and <stype>square sails</stype>. Square sails are always
bent to yards, with their foot lying across the line of the vessel.
Fore-and-aft sails are set upon stays or gaffs with their foot in line
with the keel. A fore-and-aft sail is triangular, or quadrilateral with
the after leech longer than the fore leech. Square sails are
quadrilateral, but not necessarily square. See Phrases under
<er>Fore</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and <er>Square</er>, <pos>a.</pos>; also,
<er>Bark</er>, <er>Brig</er>, <er>Schooner</er>, <er>Ship</er>,
<er>Stay</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sail burton</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a purchase
for hoisting sails aloft for bending.</cd> -- <col><b>Sail
fluke</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the whiff.</cd> -- <col><b>Sail
hook</b></col>, <cd>a small hook used in making sails, to hold the seams
square.</cd> -- <col><b>Sail loft</b></col>, <cd>a loft or room where
sails are cut out and made.</cd> -- <col><b>Sail room</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a room in a vessel where sails are stowed when
not in use.</cd> -- <col><b>Sail yard</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>the yard or spar on which a sail is extended.</cd> --
<col><b>Shoulder-of-mutton sail</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a
triangular sail of peculiar form. It is chiefly used to set on a boat's
mast.</cd> -- <col><b>To crowd sail</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld>
<cd>See under <er>Crowd</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To loose sails</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to unfurl or spread sails.</cd> -- <col><b>To
make sail</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to extend an additional
quantity of sail.</cd> -- <col><b>To set a sail</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to extend or spread a sail to the wind.</cd> --
<col><b>To set sail</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to unfurl or
spread the sails; hence, to begin a voyage.</cd> -- <col><b>To shorten
sail</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to reduce the extent of sail, or
take in a part.</cd> -- <col><b>To strike sail</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to lower the sails suddenly, as in saluting, or
in sudden gusts of wind; hence, to acknowledge inferiority; to abate
pretension.</cd> -- <col><b>Under sail</b></col>, <cd>having the sails
spread.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sail
<hw>Sail</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sailed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sailing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>segelian</ets>,
<ets>seglian</ets>. See <er>Sail</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To be impelled or driven forward by the action of wind upon sails,
as a ship on water; to be impelled on a body of water by the action of
steam or other power.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move through or on the water; to swim, as a fish
or a water fowl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be conveyed in a vessel on water; to pass by
water; <as>as, they <ex>sailed</ex> from London to
Canton</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To set sail; to begin a voyage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To move smoothly through the air; to glide through
the air without apparent exertion, as a bird.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As is a winged messenger of heaven, . . .⟦br⟧
When he bestrides the lazy pacing clouds,⟦br⟧
And <qex>sails</qex> upon the bosom of the air.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sail
<hw>Sail</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass or move upon,
as in a ship, by means of sails; hence, to move or journey upon (the
water) by means of steam or other force.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A thousand ships were manned to <qex>sail</qex> the sea.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fly through; to glide or move smoothly
through.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sublime she <qex>sails</qex>⟦br⟧
The aerial space, and mounts the wing⟦egrave⟧d gales.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To direct or manage the motion of, as a vessel;
<as>as, to <ex>sail</ex> one's own ship</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sailable</ent>⟦br⟧
